1
00:01:09,972 --> 00:01:12,012
<i>Sometimes, I think I'm cursed.</i>

2
00:01:12,172 --> 00:01:14,972
<i>Because of something that happened</i>
<i>before I was even born.</i>

3
00:01:15,972 --> 00:01:19,012
<i>See, a long time ago,</i>
<i>there was this family.</i>

4
00:01:20,332 --> 00:01:22,212
<i>The</i> papá, <i>he was a musician.</i>

5
00:01:23,212 --> 00:01:26,852
<i>He and his family would sing and dance</i>
<i>and count their blessings.</i>

6
00:01:28,172 --> 00:01:31,892
<i>But he also had a dream.</i>
<i>To play for the world.</i>

7
00:01:34,892 --> 00:01:37,052
<i>And one day,</i>

8
00:01:37,172 --> 00:01:40,852
<i>he left with his guitar</i>
<i>and never returned.</i>

9
00:01:49,532 --> 00:01:50,892
<i>And the</i> mamá...

10
00:01:51,252 --> 00:01:53,812
<i>She didn't have time to cry</i>
<i>over that walk-away musician.</i>

11
00:01:56,412 --> 00:02:01,172
<i>After banishing all music from her life</i>
<i>she found a way...</i>

12
00:02:01,332 --> 00:02:02,772
<i>to provide for her daughter.</i>

13
00:02:06,892 --> 00:02:10,092
<i>She rolled up her sleeves</i>
<i>and she learned to make shoes.</i>

14
00:02:15,412 --> 00:02:17,732
<i>She could have made candy,</i>

15
00:02:17,772 --> 00:02:20,772
<i>or fireworks, or sparkly underwear...</i>

16
00:02:20,932 --> 00:02:25,892
<i>for wrestlers, but no, she chose shoes.</i>

17
00:02:28,732 --> 00:02:30,772
<i>Then she taught her daughter</i>
<i>to make shoes.</i>

18
00:02:32,372 --> 00:02:34,692
<i>And later, she taught her son-in-law.</i>

19
00:02:36,092 --> 00:02:37,972
<i>Then her grandkids got roped in.</i>

20
00:02:39,612 --> 00:02:42,292
<i>As her family grew, so did the business.</i>

21
00:02:44,092 --> 00:02:46,612
<i>Music had torn her family apart.</i>

22
00:02:47,732 --> 00:02:49,772
<i>But shoes held them all together.</i>

23
00:02:51,652 --> 00:02:53,252
<i>You see, that woman was</i>

24
00:02:53,292 --> 00:02:55,652
<i>my great-great-grandmother,</i>
Mamá <i>Imelda.</i>

25
00:02:56,972 --> 00:02:59,252
<i>She died way before I was born.</i>

26
00:02:59,812 --> 00:03:04,332
<i>But my family still tells her story</i>
<i>every year on</i> Día de los Muertos...

27
00:03:04,492 --> 00:03:05,812
<i>the Day of the Dead.</i>

28
00:03:05,892 --> 00:03:07,252
<i>And her little girl,</i>

29
00:03:07,972 --> 00:03:10,172
<i>she's my great-grandmother,</i>
Mamá <i>Coco.</i>

30
00:03:11,172 --> 00:03:12,452
<i>Hola, Mamá</i> Coco.

31
00:03:13,012 --> 00:03:15,172
How are you, Julio?

32
00:03:15,332 --> 00:03:17,372
<i>Actually, my name is Miguel.</i>

33
00:03:17,612 --> 00:03:21,252
Mamá <i>Coco has trouble</i>
<i>remembering things.</i>

34
00:03:21,412 --> 00:03:23,412
<i>But it's good to talk to her anyway.</i>

35
00:03:23,492 --> 00:03:25,412
<i>So, I tell her pretty much everything.</i>

36
00:03:25,612 --> 00:03:27,252
I used to run like this.

37
00:03:27,332 --> 00:03:29,652
But now I run like this
which is way faster.

38
00:03:30,292 --> 00:03:33,172
And the winner is <i>Luchadora</i> Coco!

39
00:03:34,452 --> 00:03:36,652
I have a dimple on this side,
but not on this side.

40
00:03:36,692 --> 00:03:38,492
Dimple, no dimple.
Dimple, no dimple.

41
00:03:38,652 --> 00:03:40,772
Miguel, eat your food.

42
00:03:40,932 --> 00:03:43,332
<i>My</i> abuelita,
<i>she's</i> Mamá <i>Coco's daughter.</i>

43
00:03:43,492 --> 00:03:46,492
Oh, you're a twig, <i>mijo.</i>
Have some more.

44
00:03:46,652 --> 00:03:47,652
No, <i>gracias.</i>

45
00:03:47,812 --> 00:03:50,932
I asked if you would like more tamales!

46
00:03:51,092 --> 00:03:52,172
<i>Sí?</i>

47
00:03:52,332 --> 00:03:54,652
That's what I thought you said!

48
00:03:54,812 --> 00:03:56,452
Abuelita <i>runs our house</i>

49
00:03:56,532 --> 00:03:58,172
<i>just like</i> Mamá <i>Imelda did.</i>

50
00:04:01,172 --> 00:04:02,172
No music!

51
00:04:03,692 --> 00:04:04,892
No music!

52
00:04:05,052 --> 00:04:06,692
<i>♪ Y aunque la vida ♪</i>

53
00:04:06,852 --> 00:04:08,372
No music!

54
00:04:08,452 --> 00:04:10,372
<i>I think we're</i>
<i>the only family in México</i>

55
00:04:10,492 --> 00:04:11,772
<i>who hates music.</i>

56
00:04:11,972 --> 00:04:15,172
<i>And my family's fine with that. But me...</i>

57
00:04:15,492 --> 00:04:17,572
-Be back by lunch, <i>mijo.</i>
-Love you, <i>Mamá.</i>

58
00:04:19,052 --> 00:04:20,972
<i>I am not like the rest of my family!</i>

59
00:04:22,532 --> 00:04:23,892
<i>-Hola,</i> Miguel!
<i>-Hola!</i>

60
00:04:29,892 --> 00:04:32,052
<i>-Muchas gracias.</i>
<i>-De nada,</i> Miguel.

61
00:04:36,332 --> 00:04:38,492
Hey! Dante!

62
00:04:40,012 --> 00:04:43,692
Sit. Down. Roll over. Shake.

63
00:04:44,572 --> 00:04:45,652
Fist bump!

64
00:04:45,852 --> 00:04:47,732
Good boy, Dante!

65
00:04:51,652 --> 00:04:54,172
<i>I know I'm not supposed to love music.</i>

66
00:04:54,252 --> 00:04:55,572
<i>But it's not my fault!</i>

67
00:04:55,652 --> 00:04:57,692
<i>It's his!</i>

68
00:04:57,812 --> 00:04:59,612
<i>Ernesto de la Cruz.</i>

69
00:04:59,692 --> 00:05:02,452
<i>The greatest musician of all time.</i>

70
00:05:02,612 --> 00:05:04,452
Right here
in this very plaza,

71
00:05:04,532 --> 00:05:08,092
Ernesto de la Cruz took his first steps...

72
00:05:08,292 --> 00:05:11,612
toward becoming the most beloved
singer in Méxican history.

73
00:05:13,332 --> 00:05:16,252
<i>He started out a total nobody</i>
<i>from Santa Cecilia, like me.</i>

74
00:05:17,612 --> 00:05:21,452
<i>But when he played music,</i>
<i>he made people fall in love with him.</i>

75
00:05:22,052 --> 00:05:24,212
<i>He starred in movies.</i>

76
00:05:24,732 --> 00:05:28,972
<i>He had the coolest guitar!</i>
<i>He could fly!</i>

77
00:05:29,052 --> 00:05:31,332
<i>And he wrote the best songs.</i>

78
00:05:31,652 --> 00:05:33,732
<i>But my all-time favorite, it's...</i>

79
00:05:33,892 --> 00:05:37,132
<i>♪ Remember me</i>

80
00:05:37,292 --> 00:05:38,972
<i>♪ Though I have to say goodbye</i>

81
00:05:39,092 --> 00:05:40,772
<i>♪ Remember me</i>
<i>♪ Remember me</i>

82
00:05:40,932 --> 00:05:42,292
<i>♪ Don't let it make you cry</i>

83
00:05:42,372 --> 00:05:44,652
<i>♪ For even if I'm far away</i>

84
00:05:44,812 --> 00:05:48,292
<i>♪ I hold you in my heart</i>
<i>I sing a secret song to you</i>

85
00:05:48,452 --> 00:05:51,292
<i>♪ Each night we are apart</i>
<i>Remember me</i>

86
00:05:51,452 --> 00:05:53,372
<i>♪ Though I have to travel far</i>

87
00:05:53,492 --> 00:05:55,172
<i>♪ Remember me</i>
<i>♪ Remember me</i>

88
00:05:55,332 --> 00:05:56,972
<i>♪ Each time you hear a sad guitar</i>

89
00:05:57,092 --> 00:06:01,292
<i>♪ Know that I'm with you</i>
<i>the only way that I can be</i>

90
00:06:02,292 --> 00:06:05,812
<i>♪ Until you're in my arms again ♪</i>

91
00:06:06,012 --> 00:06:08,412
<i>He lived the kind of</i>
<i>life you dream about.</i>

92
00:06:12,572 --> 00:06:14,172
<i>Until 1942.</i>

93
00:06:16,172 --> 00:06:19,332
<i>When he was crushed by a giant bell.</i>

94
00:06:20,172 --> 00:06:22,652
<i>I want to be just like him.</i>

95
00:06:29,532 --> 00:06:31,572
<i>Sometimes, I look at de la Cruz</i>

96
00:06:31,652 --> 00:06:35,052
<i>and I get this feeling</i>
<i>like we're connected.</i>

97
00:06:35,332 --> 00:06:40,212
<i>Like if he could play music,</i>
<i>maybe someday, I could too.</i>

98
00:06:40,612 --> 00:06:42,892
If it wasn't for my family.

99
00:06:43,332 --> 00:06:45,212
<i>-Ay-ay-ay, muchacho.</i>
-Huh?

100
00:06:45,332 --> 00:06:47,452
I asked for a shoe shine
not your life story.

101
00:06:47,612 --> 00:06:49,612
Oh, yeah. Sorry.

102
00:06:49,692 --> 00:06:52,212
I just can't really talk about
any of this at home. So...

103
00:06:52,372 --> 00:06:54,172
If I were you,

104
00:06:54,212 --> 00:06:56,052
I'd march right up to my family and say...

105
00:06:56,212 --> 00:06:58,532
"Hey, I'm a musician. Deal with it."

106
00:06:58,732 --> 00:07:02,452
-I could never say that.
-You are a musician, no?

107
00:07:02,612 --> 00:07:03,892
I don't know.

108
00:07:04,012 --> 00:07:06,132
I mean, I only really play for myself.

109
00:07:06,212 --> 00:07:09,212
Ah! Did de la Cruz become
the world's best musician

110
00:07:09,332 --> 00:07:11,212
by hiding his skills?

111
00:07:11,332 --> 00:07:14,332
No! He walked out onto that plaza

112
00:07:14,412 --> 00:07:16,212
and he played out loud.

113
00:07:16,372 --> 00:07:18,212
<i>Mira, mira,</i> they're setting up
for tonight!

114
00:07:18,372 --> 00:07:21,252
The music competition
for <i>Día de Muertos.</i>

115
00:07:21,292 --> 00:07:23,772
You want to be like your hero?
You should sign up!

116
00:07:23,892 --> 00:07:26,172
Uh-uh. My family would freak!

117
00:07:26,332 --> 00:07:30,212
Look, if you're too scared
then, well, have fun making shoes.

118
00:07:31,332 --> 00:07:33,852
Come on,
what did de la Cruz always say?

119
00:07:34,412 --> 00:07:35,852
Seize your moment?

120
00:07:37,372 --> 00:07:39,172
Show me what you got, <i>muchacho.</i>

121
00:07:41,332 --> 00:07:42,332
I'll be your first audience.

122
00:07:49,572 --> 00:07:50,612
Miguel!

123
00:07:52,732 --> 00:07:54,452
<i>-Abuelita!</i>
-What are you doing here?

124
00:07:56,772 --> 00:07:58,212
You leave my grandson alone.

125
00:07:58,292 --> 00:07:59,292
<i>Doña,</i> please!

126
00:07:59,332 --> 00:08:00,412
I was just getting a shine.

127
00:08:00,932 --> 00:08:03,532
I know your tricks, mariachi.
What did he say to you?

128
00:08:03,612 --> 00:08:05,092
He was just showing me his guitar.

129
00:08:05,252 --> 00:08:06,292
Shame on you.

130
00:08:07,172 --> 00:08:12,252
My grandson is a sweet little
<i>angelito querido cielito.</i>

131
00:08:12,372 --> 00:08:14,972
He wants no part
of your music, mariachi.

132
00:08:15,052 --> 00:08:16,372
You keep away from him.

133
00:08:20,092 --> 00:08:23,652
<i>Ay, pobrecito.</i>
Oh, <i>estás bien, mijo.</i>

134
00:08:25,772 --> 00:08:27,892
You know better
than to be here in this place!

135
00:08:28,052 --> 00:08:31,132
You will come home. Now.

136
00:08:41,892 --> 00:08:43,012
How many times have we told you?

137
00:08:43,092 --> 00:08:45,412
That plaza is crawling with mariachis.

138
00:08:45,572 --> 00:08:47,572
Yes, <i>Tío</i> Berto.

139
00:08:47,652 --> 00:08:50,612
-No, no, no, no, no!
-Ah! Go away, you. Go!

140
00:08:50,772 --> 00:08:51,972
It's just Dante.

141
00:08:52,132 --> 00:08:54,172
Never name a street dog.

142
00:08:54,292 --> 00:08:56,012
They'll follow you forever.
Now, go get my shoe.

143
00:09:03,492 --> 00:09:06,012
I found your son in Mariachi Plaza.

144
00:09:06,172 --> 00:09:07,332
<i>Ay,</i> Miguel!

145
00:09:07,492 --> 00:09:09,652
You know how <i>Abuelita</i> feels
about the plaza.

146
00:09:09,812 --> 00:09:12,532
-I was just shining shoes.
-A musician's shoes!

147
00:09:15,332 --> 00:09:16,692
But the plaza's where
all the foot traffic is.

148
00:09:16,852 --> 00:09:20,492
If <i>Abuelita</i> says no more plaza,
then no more plaza.

149
00:09:20,612 --> 00:09:22,692
-But what about tonight?
-What's tonight?

150
00:09:22,852 --> 00:09:25,612
Well, they're having this talent show.

151
00:09:25,692 --> 00:09:27,292
And I thought I might...

152
00:09:27,932 --> 00:09:30,532
-Sign up?
-Well, maybe?

153
00:09:30,612 --> 00:09:33,612
You have to have talent
to be in a talent show.

154
00:09:33,812 --> 00:09:36,692
What are you gonna do?
Shine shoes?

155
00:09:36,772 --> 00:09:38,212
It's <i>Día de los Muertos.</i>

156
00:09:38,372 --> 00:09:41,532
No one's going anywhere.
Tonight is about family.

157
00:09:41,652 --> 00:09:44,292
<i>Ofrenda</i> room. <i>Vámonos.</i>

158
00:09:55,332 --> 00:09:57,012
Don't give me that look.

159
00:09:57,172 --> 00:09:59,892
<i>Día de los Muertos</i>
is the one night of the year

160
00:09:59,972 --> 00:10:01,852
our ancestors can come visit us.

161
00:10:02,012 --> 00:10:06,012
We've put their photos on the <i>ofrenda</i>
so their spirits can cross over.

162
00:10:06,212 --> 00:10:08,052
That is very important.

163
00:10:08,172 --> 00:10:10,372
If we don't put them up, they can't come.

164
00:10:10,572 --> 00:10:12,612
We made all this food,

165
00:10:12,692 --> 00:10:15,332
set out the things
they loved in life, <i>mijo.</i>

166
00:10:15,492 --> 00:10:18,532
All this work
to bring the family together.

167
00:10:18,692 --> 00:10:21,932
I don't want you sneaking off
to who knows where.

168
00:10:22,052 --> 00:10:23,412
Where are you going?

169
00:10:23,572 --> 00:10:24,852
I thought we were done.

170
00:10:25,012 --> 00:10:28,092
<i>Ay, Dios mio.</i> Being part of
this family means

171
00:10:28,172 --> 00:10:29,852
being here for this family.

172
00:10:30,012 --> 00:10:32,252
I don't want to see you end up like--

173
00:10:32,332 --> 00:10:33,692
Like <i>Mamá</i> Coco's <i>papá?</i>

174
00:10:33,812 --> 00:10:36,852
Never mention that man!
He's better off forgotten.

175
00:10:36,932 --> 00:10:37,932
But you're the one who--

176
00:10:38,012 --> 00:10:39,132
I was just--

177
00:10:39,212 --> 00:10:40,452
But-- I--

178
00:10:40,612 --> 00:10:41,892
<i>Papá?</i>

179
00:10:42,052 --> 00:10:43,732
<i>Papá</i> is home?

180
00:10:43,772 --> 00:10:46,612
<i>Mamá, cálmese, cálmese.</i>

181
00:10:46,772 --> 00:10:48,532
<i>Papá</i> is coming home?

182
00:10:48,692 --> 00:10:51,452
No, <i>Mamá.</i> It's okay. I'm here.

183
00:10:52,772 --> 00:10:54,372
Who are you?

184
00:10:54,532 --> 00:10:57,132
Rest, <i>Mamá.</i>

185
00:10:58,052 --> 00:11:01,132
I'm hard on you because I care, Miguel.

186
00:11:01,812 --> 00:11:03,612
Miguel? Miguel?

187
00:11:06,452 --> 00:11:08,292
What are we going to do with that boy?

188
00:11:10,012 --> 00:11:13,652
You're right.
That's just what he needs.

189
00:11:37,572 --> 00:11:39,252
It's you. Get in here.

190
00:11:39,372 --> 00:11:42,012
Come on, Dante. Hurry up!

191
00:11:42,452 --> 00:11:44,252
You're gonna get me in trouble, boy.

192
00:11:44,332 --> 00:11:45,652
Someone could hear me.

193
00:11:50,692 --> 00:11:52,452
I wish someone
wanted to hear me.

194
00:11:53,892 --> 00:11:56,772
Other than you. Ew. Okay.

195
00:11:58,532 --> 00:12:00,292
<i>Perfecto!</i>

196
00:12:33,932 --> 00:12:36,532
<i>I have to sing. I have to play!</i>

197
00:12:36,692 --> 00:12:40,972
<i>The music, it's not just in me, it is me.</i>

198
00:12:43,052 --> 00:12:45,852
<i>When life gets me down,</i>
<i>I play my guitar.</i>

199
00:12:47,132 --> 00:12:49,372
<i>The rest of the world</i>
<i>may follow the rules,</i>

200
00:12:49,412 --> 00:12:51,892
<i>but I must follow my heart.</i>

201
00:12:52,732 --> 00:12:53,772
Ugh!

202
00:12:53,892 --> 00:12:56,892
<i>You know that feeling</i>
<i>like there's a song in the air and...</i>

203
00:12:57,012 --> 00:12:58,412
<i>it's playing just for you?</i>

204
00:13:02,412 --> 00:13:05,412
<i>♪ A feeling so close...</i>

205
00:13:06,172 --> 00:13:10,172
<i>♪ You could reach out and touch it</i>

206
00:13:10,532 --> 00:13:12,252
<i>♪ I never knew</i>

207
00:13:12,372 --> 00:13:16,172
<i>♪ I could want something</i>
<i>so much, but it's true</i>

208
00:13:17,492 --> 00:13:18,852
<i>You must have faith, sister.</i>

209
00:13:19,012 --> 00:13:21,412
<i>Oh, but,</i> Padre, <i>he will never listen.</i>

210
00:13:21,572 --> 00:13:23,172
<i>He will listen. To music.</i>

211
00:13:23,332 --> 00:13:29,332
<i>♪ Only a song, only a song has</i>
<i>the power to change a heart ♪</i>

212
00:13:34,012 --> 00:13:36,772
<i>Never underestimate</i>
<i>the power of music.</i>

213
00:13:41,372 --> 00:13:43,772
<i>But my father,</i>
<i>he will never give his permission.</i>

214
00:13:44,772 --> 00:13:46,412
<i>I am done</i>
<i>asking permission.</i>

215
00:13:46,572 --> 00:13:49,372
<i>When you see your moment,</i>
<i>you mustn't let it pass you by.</i>

216
00:13:49,532 --> 00:13:51,252
<i>You must seize it!</i>

217
00:13:51,412 --> 00:13:52,932
Señor <i>de la Cruz,</i>

218
00:13:52,972 --> 00:13:55,372
<i>what did it take for you</i>
<i>to seize your moment?</i>

219
00:13:57,212 --> 00:14:00,052
<i>I had to have faith in my dream.</i>

220
00:14:00,132 --> 00:14:01,932
<i>No one was going to hand it to me.</i>

221
00:14:02,052 --> 00:14:04,252
<i>It was up to me to reach for that dream.</i>

222
00:14:04,452 --> 00:14:06,292
<i>Grab it tight and make it come true.</i>

223
00:14:06,412 --> 00:14:07,812
<i>...and make it come true.</i>

224
00:14:12,572 --> 00:14:15,932
No more hiding, Dante.
I got to seize my moment!

225
00:14:17,292 --> 00:14:20,412
I'm gonna play in Mariachi Plaza
if it kills me.

226
00:14:23,892 --> 00:14:26,732
<i>Día de los Muertos</i> has begun!

227
00:14:27,412 --> 00:14:30,572
No, no. We have to make a clear path.

228
00:14:30,772 --> 00:14:33,252
The petals guide our ancestors home.

229
00:14:33,332 --> 00:14:35,172
We don't want their spirits to get lost.

230
00:14:35,332 --> 00:14:37,932
We want them to come
and enjoy all the food

231
00:14:38,012 --> 00:14:39,332
and drinks on the <i>ofrenda.</i>

232
00:14:40,812 --> 00:14:41,892
<i>Mamá!</i>

233
00:14:42,012 --> 00:14:43,332
Where should we put this table?

234
00:14:43,532 --> 00:14:45,012
In the courtyard, <i>mijos.</i>

235
00:14:45,052 --> 00:14:46,172
You want it down by the kitchen?

236
00:14:46,372 --> 00:14:48,292
<i>Sí.</i> Next to the other one.

237
00:14:51,332 --> 00:14:54,092
-Get under! Get under!
-Miguel?

238
00:14:54,292 --> 00:14:57,652
Nothing! <i>Mamá, Papá.</i> I--

239
00:14:57,812 --> 00:15:02,492
Miguel, your <i>abuelita</i> had
the most wonderful idea.

240
00:15:02,652 --> 00:15:06,772
We've all decided.
It's time you joined us in the workshop!

241
00:15:06,972 --> 00:15:09,132
-What?
-No more shining shoes.

242
00:15:09,292 --> 00:15:12,052
You'll be making them
every day after school.

243
00:15:12,212 --> 00:15:15,212
Oh! Our Migueli-ti-ti-ti-to

244
00:15:15,292 --> 00:15:17,892
carrying on the family tradition.

245
00:15:18,012 --> 00:15:20,372
And on <i>Día de los Muertos!</i>

246
00:15:20,452 --> 00:15:22,892
Your ancestors will be so proud.

247
00:15:23,212 --> 00:15:26,572
You'll craft huaraches
just like your <i>Tía</i> Victoria.

248
00:15:26,732 --> 00:15:29,412
And wingtips
like your <i>Papá</i> Julio.

249
00:15:29,572 --> 00:15:31,892
But what if
I'm no good at making shoes?

250
00:15:31,972 --> 00:15:35,532
Ah, Miguel. You have your
family here to guide you.

251
00:15:36,212 --> 00:15:37,892
You are a Rivera.

252
00:15:38,052 --> 00:15:39,812
And a Rivera is...

253
00:15:41,572 --> 00:15:44,212
A shoemaker. Through and through.

254
00:15:44,372 --> 00:15:47,252
That's my boy! Berto!

255
00:15:47,412 --> 00:15:49,572
Break out the good stuff.
I want to make a toast.

256
00:16:00,252 --> 00:16:03,772
Dante! No, Dante. Stop!

257
00:16:14,292 --> 00:16:17,252
No, no, no, no, no! No.

258
00:16:29,452 --> 00:16:31,612
De la Cruz's guitar?

259
00:16:31,812 --> 00:16:34,972
<i>Papá? Papá?</i>

260
00:16:36,292 --> 00:16:40,092
<i>Mamá</i> Coco,
is your <i>papá</i> Ernesto de la Cruz?

261
00:16:40,252 --> 00:16:42,652
<i>Papá! Papá!</i>

262
00:16:54,572 --> 00:16:56,572
<i>Papá! Papá!</i> It's him!

263
00:16:56,732 --> 00:16:58,452
I know who my
great-great-grandfather was.

264
00:16:58,572 --> 00:17:00,132
Miguel, get down from there.

265
00:17:00,332 --> 00:17:02,492
<i>Mamá</i> Coco's father
was Ernesto de la Cruz!

266
00:17:02,652 --> 00:17:03,972
What are you talking about?

267
00:17:04,172 --> 00:17:06,452
I'm gonna be a musician!

268
00:17:08,452 --> 00:17:09,772
What is all this?

269
00:17:09,812 --> 00:17:11,772
You keep secrets from your own family?

270
00:17:12,372 --> 00:17:14,052
It's all that time he spends in the plaza.

271
00:17:14,132 --> 00:17:15,492
Fills his head with crazy fantasies.

272
00:17:15,612 --> 00:17:17,012
It's not a fantasy.

273
00:17:17,172 --> 00:17:19,332
That man was Ernesto de la Cruz!

274
00:17:19,452 --> 00:17:21,132
The greatest musician of all time!

275
00:17:21,292 --> 00:17:22,812
We've never known anything
about this man!

276
00:17:22,972 --> 00:17:26,372
But whoever he was,
he still abandoned his family.

277
00:17:26,532 --> 00:17:28,132
This is no future for my son.

278
00:17:28,172 --> 00:17:30,692
But, <i>Papá,</i> you said
my family would guide me.

279
00:17:30,852 --> 00:17:33,132
Well, de la Cruz is my family.

280
00:17:33,332 --> 00:17:34,812
I'm supposed to play music.

281
00:17:34,972 --> 00:17:37,172
Never! That man's music was a curse.

282
00:17:37,372 --> 00:17:38,972
I will not allow it.

283
00:17:39,172 --> 00:17:40,652
-If you would just let--
-Miguel...

284
00:17:40,812 --> 00:17:42,252
You will listen to your family.

285
00:17:42,332 --> 00:17:43,532
No more music.

286
00:17:43,692 --> 00:17:46,252
-Just listen to me play!
-End of argument.

287
00:17:48,652 --> 00:17:51,092
You want to end up
like that man? Forgotten?

288
00:17:51,252 --> 00:17:53,572
Left off your family's <i>ofrenda?</i>

289
00:17:53,732 --> 00:17:55,532
I don't care if I'm on
some stupid <i>ofrenda.</i>

290
00:17:59,732 --> 00:18:00,852
-No!
<i>-Mamá!</i>

291
00:18:05,572 --> 00:18:08,852
There. No guitar. No music.

292
00:18:11,732 --> 00:18:16,452
Oh, come. You'll feel better
after you eat with your family.

293
00:18:16,612 --> 00:18:18,412
I don't want to be in this family!

294
00:18:18,812 --> 00:18:20,732
Miguel! Miguel!

295
00:18:39,612 --> 00:18:42,412
I want to play in the plaza,
like de la Cruz.

296
00:18:42,452 --> 00:18:43,572
Can I still sign up?

297
00:18:43,772 --> 00:18:44,932
You got an instrument?

298
00:18:45,132 --> 00:18:47,812
No.
But if I can borrow a guitar...

299
00:18:47,972 --> 00:18:49,492
Musicians got to bring
their own instruments.

300
00:18:49,612 --> 00:18:51,172
You find a guitar, kid,

301
00:18:51,332 --> 00:18:52,612
I'll put you on the list.

302
00:18:55,092 --> 00:18:58,292
-Can I borrow your guitar?
-Sorry, <i>muchacho.</i>

303
00:18:58,452 --> 00:19:00,772
-You guys have a spare guitar?
-No.

304
00:19:01,452 --> 00:19:03,492
I need a guitar just for a little bit.

305
00:19:03,612 --> 00:19:05,892
Get out of here, kid.

306
00:19:18,132 --> 00:19:22,452
Great-great-grandfather,
what am I supposed to do?

307
00:20:00,092 --> 00:20:01,132
No, no, no, no.

308
00:20:01,292 --> 00:20:03,732
Dante, stop! <i>Cállate!</i> Shh!

309
00:20:25,892 --> 00:20:27,172
I'm sorry.

310
00:21:03,612 --> 00:21:07,372
<i>Señor</i> de la Cruz, please don't be mad.

311
00:21:07,412 --> 00:21:08,692
I'm Miguel.

312
00:21:08,852 --> 00:21:13,252
Your great-great grandson.
I need to borrow this.

313
00:21:16,412 --> 00:21:18,932
Our family thinks
music is a curse.

314
00:21:19,092 --> 00:21:22,252
None of them understand
but I know you would have.

315
00:21:22,932 --> 00:21:25,572
You would have told me
to follow my heart.

316
00:21:25,612 --> 00:21:27,052
To seize my moment!

317
00:21:28,412 --> 00:21:30,452
So, if it's all right with you,

318
00:21:31,372 --> 00:21:33,892
I'm gonna play in the plaza.
Just like you did!

319
00:21:41,932 --> 00:21:44,812
The guitar! It's gone!

320
00:21:44,932 --> 00:21:46,772
Somebody stole
de la Cruz's guitar!

321
00:21:47,252 --> 00:21:49,012
The window's broken. Look!

322
00:21:53,932 --> 00:21:55,292
All right, who's in there?

323
00:21:55,612 --> 00:21:57,332
I'm sorry. It's not what it looks like.

324
00:21:57,452 --> 00:21:58,652
De la Cruz is my--

325
00:22:00,172 --> 00:22:02,132
There's nobody here.

326
00:22:17,812 --> 00:22:19,132
- Miguel!
<i>- Mamá!</i>

327
00:22:19,292 --> 00:22:23,772
Miguel, come home.
Where are you, Miguel?

328
00:22:27,092 --> 00:22:30,412
<i>Dios mio!</i> Little boy. Are you okay?

329
00:22:30,612 --> 00:22:32,012
Here. Let me help you.

330
00:22:33,372 --> 00:22:34,372
Thanks. I--

331
00:22:45,332 --> 00:22:47,332
Do you mind? Whoa!

332
00:23:08,052 --> 00:23:10,732
Look how big she's getting.

333
00:23:13,972 --> 00:23:15,372
Dante!

334
00:23:15,852 --> 00:23:18,732
You can see me? Wait!

335
00:23:18,852 --> 00:23:21,532
What's going on? Dante!

336
00:23:24,052 --> 00:23:26,052
-Oh, I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
-Miguel?

337
00:23:26,212 --> 00:23:27,532
-Miguel?
-Miguel?

338
00:23:31,372 --> 00:23:34,892
You're here? Here, here.
And you can see us?

339
00:23:35,052 --> 00:23:37,372
Our Migueli-ti-ti-ti-to!

340
00:23:37,532 --> 00:23:38,732
Remind me how I know you.

341
00:23:38,892 --> 00:23:41,412
We're your family, <i>mijo.</i>

342
00:23:43,612 --> 00:23:45,612
<i>- Tía</i> Rosita?
<i>- Sí.</i>

343
00:23:47,772 --> 00:23:49,732
<i>- Papá</i> Julio?
<i>- Hola.</i>

344
00:23:50,812 --> 00:23:52,212
<i>Tía</i> Victoria?

345
00:23:52,412 --> 00:23:54,692
He doesn't seem entirely dead.

346
00:23:54,732 --> 00:23:57,492
He's not quite alive either.

347
00:23:57,612 --> 00:24:00,252
We need <i>Mamá</i> Imelda.
She'll know how to fix this.

348
00:24:00,412 --> 00:24:04,252
<i>Oye!</i> It's <i>Mamá</i> Imelda.

349
00:24:04,412 --> 00:24:05,412
She couldn't cross over.

350
00:24:05,612 --> 00:24:07,692
-She's stuck!
-On the other side!

351
00:24:07,892 --> 00:24:10,532
<i>Tío</i> Oscar? <i>Tío</i> Felipe?

352
00:24:10,932 --> 00:24:12,772
Oh. Hey, Miguel.

353
00:24:12,972 --> 00:24:15,532
I have a feeling this has
something to do with you.

354
00:24:15,572 --> 00:24:17,572
But if <i>Mamá</i> Imelda can't come to us...

355
00:24:17,772 --> 00:24:19,812
Then we are going to her. <i>Vámonos!</i>

356
00:24:33,972 --> 00:24:35,412
Whoa.

357
00:24:35,452 --> 00:24:37,732
Come on, Miguel. It's okay.

358
00:24:51,212 --> 00:24:55,452
Dante? Dante! Dante, wait up!

359
00:24:57,612 --> 00:25:02,372
You got to stay with me, boy.
We don't know... where...

360
00:25:22,932 --> 00:25:26,372
This isn't a dream then.
You're all really out there.

361
00:25:26,492 --> 00:25:28,332
-You thought we weren't?
-Well, I don't know.

362
00:25:28,492 --> 00:25:32,492
I thought it might've been one of those
made up things that adults tell kids.

363
00:25:32,612 --> 00:25:33,612
Like vitamins.

364
00:25:33,652 --> 00:25:35,692
Miguel, vitamins are a real thing.

365
00:25:35,852 --> 00:25:37,492
Well, now I'm thinking
maybe they could be.

366
00:25:38,052 --> 00:25:40,052
<i>Mija,</i> it's not nice to stare at--

367
00:25:40,172 --> 00:25:41,452
<i>Ay!</i> Santa Maria!

368
00:25:49,612 --> 00:25:53,692
Are those... Alebrijes! But those are--

369
00:25:53,812 --> 00:25:56,572
Real alebrijes. Spirit creatures.

370
00:25:56,732 --> 00:25:58,292
They guide souls on their journey.

371
00:25:58,372 --> 00:26:00,292
Watch your step.
They make <i>caquitas</i> everywhere.

372
00:26:00,452 --> 00:26:02,852
<i>Welcome back</i>
<i>to the Land of the Dead.</i>

373
00:26:02,892 --> 00:26:05,652
<i>Please have all offerings</i>
<i>ready for re-entry.</i>

374
00:26:05,692 --> 00:26:07,812
Welcome back.
Anything to declare?

375
00:26:07,972 --> 00:26:09,412
Some churros. From my family.

376
00:26:09,572 --> 00:26:11,412
How wonderful. Next.

377
00:26:11,572 --> 00:26:13,372
<i>If you are</i>
<i>experiencing travel issues,</i>

378
00:26:13,412 --> 00:26:14,932
<i>agents at the Department of Family...</i>

379
00:26:15,092 --> 00:26:17,252
<i>Reunions are available to assist you.</i>

380
00:26:17,532 --> 00:26:19,332
Next family, please.

381
00:26:22,732 --> 00:26:25,092
Oh! Your photos are
on your son's <i>ofrenda.</i>

382
00:26:25,252 --> 00:26:26,492
Have a great visit.

383
00:26:26,532 --> 00:26:27,572
<i>Gracias.</i>

384
00:26:27,772 --> 00:26:29,732
<i>And remember</i>
<i>to return before sunrise.</i>

385
00:26:29,772 --> 00:26:30,852
<i>Enjoy your visit.</i>

386
00:26:31,012 --> 00:26:33,412
Next.

387
00:26:33,412 --> 00:26:36,692
Your photo's on your dentist's
<i>ofrenda.</i> Enjoy your visit.

388
00:26:36,852 --> 00:26:38,452
<i>-Gracias.</i>
-Next?

389
00:26:40,932 --> 00:26:43,052
Yes! It is I. Frida Kahlo.

390
00:26:43,252 --> 00:26:44,692
Shall we skip the scanner?

391
00:26:44,812 --> 00:26:48,252
I'm on so many <i>ofrendas</i>
it'll just overwhelm your blinky thingy.

392
00:26:50,252 --> 00:26:54,572
Well, shoot, looks like no one
put up your photo, Frida.

393
00:26:54,692 --> 00:26:58,932
Okay, when I said I was Frida,
just now, that was a lie.

394
00:26:59,092 --> 00:27:00,412
And I apologize for doing that.

395
00:27:00,572 --> 00:27:03,212
No photo on an <i>ofrenda,</i>
no crossing the bridge.

396
00:27:03,372 --> 00:27:06,772
I'm just gonna zip right over.
You won't even know I'm gone.

397
00:27:07,932 --> 00:27:10,212
Hey!

398
00:27:15,772 --> 00:27:19,412
Almost...there. Just a little further.

399
00:27:24,452 --> 00:27:25,612
Upsy-daisy...

400
00:27:25,772 --> 00:27:28,132
Fine. Okay. Fine, who cares?

401
00:27:28,172 --> 00:27:29,652
Dumb flower bridge!

402
00:27:29,732 --> 00:27:33,652
Aw. I don't know what I'd do
if no one put up my photo.

403
00:27:33,852 --> 00:27:36,132
- Next?
- Oh! Come, <i>mijo.</i> It's our turn.

404
00:27:36,292 --> 00:27:38,612
Welcome back, <i>amigos.</i>
Anything to declare?

405
00:27:38,652 --> 00:27:41,812
As a matter of fact, yes.

406
00:27:42,892 --> 00:27:43,892
<i>Hola.</i>

407
00:27:51,132 --> 00:27:53,252
<i>Paging Marta Gonzales-Ramos.</i>

408
00:27:53,292 --> 00:27:55,812
<i>Please report to Level Seven.</i>

409
00:28:00,532 --> 00:28:01,812
Whoa!

410
00:28:05,452 --> 00:28:06,972
I miss my nose.

411
00:28:17,612 --> 00:28:18,612
Come on, help us out, <i>amigo.</i>

412
00:28:18,652 --> 00:28:20,252
We got to get to
a dozen <i>ofrendas</i> tonight.

413
00:28:20,332 --> 00:28:23,852
We are not visiting your ex-wife's family
for <i>Día de Muertos!</i>

414
00:28:24,012 --> 00:28:26,492
I demand to speak
to the person in charge!

415
00:28:26,692 --> 00:28:29,492
I'm sorry, <i>señora,</i>
it says here no one put up your photo.

416
00:28:29,532 --> 00:28:33,852
My family always puts my photo
on the <i>ofrenda.</i>

417
00:28:34,012 --> 00:28:36,532
That devil box tells you nothing but lies!

418
00:28:36,692 --> 00:28:41,732
<i>- Mamá</i> Imelda?
- Oh, <i>mi familia!</i>

419
00:28:41,852 --> 00:28:43,372
They wouldn't let me cross the bridge.

420
00:28:43,612 --> 00:28:45,932
Tell this woman and her devil box

421
00:28:46,012 --> 00:28:48,532
that my photo is on the <i>ofrenda.</i>

422
00:28:48,692 --> 00:28:51,852
Well, we never
made it to the <i>ofrenda.</i>

423
00:28:52,052 --> 00:28:55,492
- What?
- We ran into...

424
00:28:58,492 --> 00:29:01,252
- Miguel?
<i>- Mamá</i> Imelda.

425
00:29:01,932 --> 00:29:04,052
What is going on?

426
00:29:04,172 --> 00:29:06,012
You the Rivera family?

427
00:29:08,292 --> 00:29:09,652
Well, you're cursed.

428
00:29:09,732 --> 00:29:10,772
What?

429
00:29:10,892 --> 00:29:13,332
<i>Día de los Muertos</i> is
the night to give to the dead.

430
00:29:13,372 --> 00:29:14,852
You stole from the dead!

431
00:29:14,892 --> 00:29:16,252
But I wasn't stealing the guitar.

432
00:29:16,372 --> 00:29:17,412
Guitar?

433
00:29:17,572 --> 00:29:18,932
It was my great-great-grandfather's.

434
00:29:19,052 --> 00:29:20,372
He would have wanted me to have it.

435
00:29:20,372 --> 00:29:23,532
Ah, ah, ah. We do not speak
of that musician.

436
00:29:23,572 --> 00:29:25,052
He is dead to this family.

437
00:29:25,252 --> 00:29:27,012
Uh, you're all dead.

438
00:29:28,292 --> 00:29:30,732
I am sorry. Whose alebrije is that?

439
00:29:30,892 --> 00:29:32,012
That's just Dante.

440
00:29:32,212 --> 00:29:34,252
He sure doesn't look like an alebrije.

441
00:29:34,412 --> 00:29:35,732
He just looks like a plain old dog.

442
00:29:35,892 --> 00:29:38,092
Or a sausage someone dropped
in a barbershop.

443
00:29:38,252 --> 00:29:41,732
Whatever he is,
I am terribly allergic.

444
00:29:41,892 --> 00:29:43,612
But Dante doesn't have any hair.

445
00:29:43,812 --> 00:29:46,332
And I don't have a nose,
and yet, here we are.

446
00:29:48,252 --> 00:29:51,172
But none of this explains
why I couldn't cross over.

447
00:29:51,252 --> 00:29:52,772
Oh!

448
00:29:55,092 --> 00:29:57,052
You took my photo off the <i>ofrenda?</i>

449
00:29:57,092 --> 00:29:59,612
-It was an accident!
-How do we send him back?

450
00:29:59,772 --> 00:30:01,852
Well,
since it's a family matter...

451
00:30:01,932 --> 00:30:04,292
the way to undo a family curse

452
00:30:04,492 --> 00:30:06,972
-is to get your family's blessing.
-That's it?

453
00:30:07,132 --> 00:30:08,572
Get your family's blessing

454
00:30:08,612 --> 00:30:10,932
and everything should go
back to normal.

455
00:30:11,092 --> 00:30:12,972
But you got to do it by sunrise.

456
00:30:13,172 --> 00:30:14,892
What happens at sunrise?

457
00:30:15,092 --> 00:30:16,732
<i>Híjole!</i> Your hand!

458
00:30:21,972 --> 00:30:24,572
Whoa, Miguel,
can't have you fainting on us.

459
00:30:24,932 --> 00:30:27,572
But not to worry.
Your family's here.

460
00:30:27,612 --> 00:30:29,492
You can get your blessing right now.

461
00:30:29,652 --> 00:30:34,612
<i>Cempasúchil, cempasúchil.</i>
Aha! <i>Perdón, señora.</i>

462
00:30:34,612 --> 00:30:35,652
Oh.

463
00:30:35,812 --> 00:30:38,132
Now, you look at the living
and say his name.

464
00:30:39,332 --> 00:30:40,332
Miguel.

465
00:30:40,452 --> 00:30:43,652
Nailed it. Now say,
"I give you my blessing."

466
00:30:43,812 --> 00:30:45,492
I give you my blessing.

467
00:30:48,132 --> 00:30:50,972
I give you my blessing to go home...

468
00:30:51,612 --> 00:30:54,812
to put my photo back on the <i>ofrenda,</i>

469
00:30:55,012 --> 00:30:56,852
and to never play music again.

470
00:30:57,092 --> 00:30:58,772
What? She can't do that!

471
00:30:58,932 --> 00:31:01,972
Well, technically, she can add
any condition she wants.

472
00:31:02,292 --> 00:31:04,332
Fine.

473
00:31:04,412 --> 00:31:06,332
Then you hand
the petal to Miguel.

474
00:31:19,092 --> 00:31:20,172
No skeletons!

475
00:31:24,692 --> 00:31:26,612
Mariachi Plaza, here I come.

476
00:31:31,012 --> 00:31:33,132
Two seconds and you already
break your promise.

477
00:31:33,332 --> 00:31:36,492
This isn't fair. It's my life.
You already had yours.

478
00:31:37,172 --> 00:31:39,172
<i>Papá</i> Julio, I ask for your blessing.

479
00:31:39,212 --> 00:31:42,212
<i>Tía</i> Rosita? Oscar?

480
00:31:42,372 --> 00:31:44,532
Felipe? <i>Tía</i> Victoria?

481
00:31:45,212 --> 00:31:49,532
Don't make this hard, <i>mijo.</i>
You go home my way or no way.

482
00:31:49,692 --> 00:31:51,372
You really hate music that much?

483
00:31:51,532 --> 00:31:54,292
I will not let you go down
the same path he did.

484
00:31:57,172 --> 00:32:01,172
The same path he did. He's family.

485
00:32:01,212 --> 00:32:02,892
Listen to your <i>Mamá</i> Imelda.

486
00:32:02,972 --> 00:32:04,172
She's just looking out for you.

487
00:32:04,332 --> 00:32:05,412
Be reasonable.

488
00:32:05,572 --> 00:32:08,732
<i>Con permiso,</i>
I need to visit the restroom.

489
00:32:08,812 --> 00:32:10,532
Be right back.

490
00:32:11,212 --> 00:32:13,252
Uh, should we tell him
there are no restrooms

491
00:32:13,332 --> 00:32:14,212
in the Land of the Dead?

492
00:32:27,892 --> 00:32:29,092
<i>Vámonos.</i>

493
00:32:29,252 --> 00:32:31,572
We got a family
looking for a living boy.

494
00:32:31,732 --> 00:32:34,252
If I want to be a musician,
I need a musician's blessing.

495
00:32:34,412 --> 00:32:36,332
We got to find my great-great-grandpa.

496
00:32:36,492 --> 00:32:38,172
Hold it, <i>muchacho.</i>

497
00:32:42,092 --> 00:32:43,412
I found that living boy!

498
00:32:43,492 --> 00:32:45,692
Oh, whoa, excuse me. Excuse me, folks.

499
00:32:45,812 --> 00:32:46,852
Excuse me.

500
00:32:47,932 --> 00:32:48,932
Oh.

501
00:32:53,052 --> 00:32:54,612
No, no. Dante!

502
00:32:55,372 --> 00:32:58,372
Disturbing the peace. Fleeing an officer.

503
00:32:58,452 --> 00:33:00,132
Falsifying a unibrow.

504
00:33:00,292 --> 00:33:02,452
-That's illegal?
-Very illegal.

505
00:33:02,612 --> 00:33:04,572
You need to clean up your act, <i>amigo.</i>

506
00:33:04,732 --> 00:33:08,292
<i>Amigo?</i> Oh, that's so nice
to hear you say that

507
00:33:08,412 --> 00:33:09,972
because I have just had a...

508
00:33:10,132 --> 00:33:12,852
really hard <i>Día de Muertos</i>
and I could really use

509
00:33:12,972 --> 00:33:14,132
an <i>amigo</i> right now.

510
00:33:14,292 --> 00:33:16,812
And <i>amigos,</i> they help their <i>amigos.</i>

511
00:33:16,972 --> 00:33:20,972
You get me across that bridge tonight,
and I'll make it worth your while.

512
00:33:21,132 --> 00:33:23,812
Oh! You like de la Cruz?
He and I go way back.

513
00:33:24,252 --> 00:33:27,092
I can get you front row seats
to his Sunrise Spectacular show.

514
00:33:27,292 --> 00:33:29,772
I'll get you backstage.
You can meet him.

515
00:33:29,932 --> 00:33:31,452
You just got to let me cross that bridge!

516
00:33:31,572 --> 00:33:33,652
I should lock you up
for the rest of the holiday.

517
00:33:33,812 --> 00:33:37,732
But my shift's almost up
and I want to visit my living family.

518
00:33:37,892 --> 00:33:40,132
So I'm letting you off with a warning.

519
00:33:41,492 --> 00:33:43,612
Can I at least get my costume back?

520
00:33:43,652 --> 00:33:45,252
Uh... No.

521
00:33:45,452 --> 00:33:47,652
Some <i>amigo.</i>

522
00:33:50,332 --> 00:33:53,812
Hey! Hey! You really know de la Cruz?

523
00:33:53,972 --> 00:33:56,332
Who wants to-- Ahh! <i>Ay!</i> You're alive!

524
00:33:56,492 --> 00:33:58,012
Shh! Yeah, I'm alive.

525
00:33:58,132 --> 00:34:00,012
And if I want to get back to
the Land of the Living...

526
00:34:00,172 --> 00:34:01,572
I need de la Cruz's blessing.

527
00:34:01,772 --> 00:34:03,092
That's weirdly specific.

528
00:34:03,252 --> 00:34:04,492
He's my great-great-grandfather.

529
00:34:04,692 --> 00:34:07,012
He's your Gr-- What?

530
00:34:07,932 --> 00:34:08,932
Ugh.

531
00:34:09,852 --> 00:34:13,332
Wait, wait, wait. Wait, wait.

532
00:34:14,532 --> 00:34:16,452
Wait. No, wait, wait, wait.

533
00:34:16,612 --> 00:34:20,612
Wait! Yes! You're going back
to the Land of the Living!

534
00:34:20,772 --> 00:34:22,652
You know what?
Maybe this isn't such a good--

535
00:34:22,812 --> 00:34:25,332
No, no, <i>niño! Niño, niño,</i>
I can help you. You can help me.

536
00:34:25,492 --> 00:34:26,532
We can help each other.

537
00:34:26,652 --> 00:34:28,332
But most importantly, you can help me.

538
00:34:28,492 --> 00:34:29,972
-Miguel!
-I'm Héctor.

539
00:34:30,092 --> 00:34:31,172
That's nice.

540
00:34:36,132 --> 00:34:37,532
<i>Espérame, chamaco!</i>

541
00:34:45,732 --> 00:34:48,052
<i>Ay,</i> he is going to get himself killed.

542
00:34:48,212 --> 00:34:51,572
I need my spirit guide...
Pepita.

543
00:35:03,572 --> 00:35:05,492
Who has that petal Miguel touched?

544
00:35:05,652 --> 00:35:08,412
Here. Nice alebrije.

545
00:35:21,412 --> 00:35:26,012
<i>Ay, ay,</i> hold still. Look up.
<i>A ver, a ver.</i> Look up, up, up.

546
00:35:27,572 --> 00:35:31,892
<i>Aqui arriba, eso...</i> Eh, <i>la rayita.</i>

547
00:35:32,532 --> 00:35:34,892
Okay. Hey! Ta-da!

548
00:35:35,892 --> 00:35:37,252
Dead as a doorknob.

549
00:35:38,612 --> 00:35:41,612
So listen, Miguel,
this place runs on memories.

550
00:35:41,772 --> 00:35:42,932
When you're well remembered,

551
00:35:43,052 --> 00:35:44,732
people put up your photo
and you get to...

552
00:35:44,892 --> 00:35:48,772
cross the bridge and visit the living
on <i>Día de Muertos.</i> Unless you're me.

553
00:35:48,932 --> 00:35:50,532
You don't get to cross over?

554
00:35:50,692 --> 00:35:52,052
No one's ever put up my picture.

555
00:35:52,132 --> 00:35:53,492
But you can change that!

556
00:35:54,092 --> 00:35:55,612
This is you?

557
00:35:55,772 --> 00:35:57,132
Eh, <i>muy guapo,</i> eh?

558
00:35:57,292 --> 00:36:00,292
So, you get me
to my great-great-grandpa...

559
00:36:00,452 --> 00:36:03,132
then I put up your photo
when I get home?

560
00:36:03,292 --> 00:36:06,972
Such a smart boy! Yes!
Great idea, yes! One hiccup.

561
00:36:07,132 --> 00:36:08,972
De la Cruz is a tough guy to get to

562
00:36:09,092 --> 00:36:10,652
and I need to cross the bridge soon.

563
00:36:10,812 --> 00:36:11,932
Like, tonight.

564
00:36:11,972 --> 00:36:13,652
So, you got any other
family here, you know?

565
00:36:13,812 --> 00:36:15,812
Someone a bit more, eh, accessible?

566
00:36:15,972 --> 00:36:17,612
Mmm... Nope.

567
00:36:17,772 --> 00:36:19,092
Don't yank my chain, <i>chamaco.</i>

568
00:36:19,132 --> 00:36:20,492
You got to have some other family.

569
00:36:20,652 --> 00:36:21,972
Only de la Cruz.

570
00:36:22,052 --> 00:36:24,052
If you can't help me,
I'll find him myself.

571
00:36:25,412 --> 00:36:27,892
Oh! Okay. Okay, kid. Fine! Fine!

572
00:36:27,972 --> 00:36:29,612
I'll get you to your great-great-grandpa.

573
00:36:31,412 --> 00:36:32,932
It's not gonna be easy, you know?

574
00:36:33,012 --> 00:36:36,012
He's a busy man. What are you doing?

575
00:36:36,172 --> 00:36:38,612
I'm walking like a skeleton. Blending in.

576
00:36:38,772 --> 00:36:40,332
No. Skeletons don't walk like that.

577
00:36:40,492 --> 00:36:44,012
-It's how you walk.
-No, I don't! Stop it!

578
00:36:44,612 --> 00:36:48,612
Whoa! Ernesto de la Cruz's
Sunrise Spectacular?

579
00:36:48,732 --> 00:36:50,172
<i>Qué padre!</i>

580
00:36:50,252 --> 00:36:53,292
Every year your great-great-grandpa
puts on that dumb show...

581
00:36:53,492 --> 00:36:54,852
to mark the end of <i>Día de Muertos.</i>

582
00:36:55,012 --> 00:36:57,332
-And you can get us in!
-Um...

583
00:36:57,492 --> 00:36:59,612
Hey, you said you have front row tickets!

584
00:36:59,692 --> 00:37:02,372
That...was a lie. I apologize for that.

585
00:37:03,012 --> 00:37:05,172
Cool off, <i>chamaco.</i>
Come on. I'll get you to him.

586
00:37:05,252 --> 00:37:06,212
How?

587
00:37:06,332 --> 00:37:08,132
Because I happen to know
where he's rehearsing.

588
00:37:19,132 --> 00:37:23,012
<i>♪ Remember me</i>
<i>Don't let it make you cry ♪</i>

589
00:37:24,292 --> 00:37:26,452
You better have
my dress, Héctor.

590
00:37:26,612 --> 00:37:27,732
<i>Hola,</i> Ceci.

591
00:37:33,892 --> 00:37:38,052
<i>-Hola.</i>
-Ceci, I lost the dress.

592
00:37:38,212 --> 00:37:39,652
<i>Ya lo sabía!</i>

593
00:37:39,812 --> 00:37:42,012
I got to dress forty dancers by sunrise.

594
00:37:42,172 --> 00:37:45,052
Thanks to you, I'm one Frida
short of an opening number!

595
00:37:46,012 --> 00:37:49,732
Dante! We shouldn't be in here.

596
00:38:05,012 --> 00:38:07,052
No, no, Dante! <i>Ven acá!</i>

597
00:38:16,172 --> 00:38:17,852
You! How did you get in here?

598
00:38:18,012 --> 00:38:22,132
-I just followed my--
-Oh! The mighty Xolo dog!

599
00:38:22,372 --> 00:38:25,092
Guider of wandering spirits.

600
00:38:25,172 --> 00:38:28,092
And whose spirit
have you guided to me?

601
00:38:28,292 --> 00:38:30,412
I don't think he's a spirit guide.

602
00:38:30,452 --> 00:38:31,532
Ah, ah, ah.

603
00:38:31,732 --> 00:38:34,492
The alebrijes of this world
can take many forms.

604
00:38:34,572 --> 00:38:37,532
They are as mysterious
as they are powerful.

605
00:38:43,452 --> 00:38:47,132
Or maybe he's just a dog.
Come, I need your eyes.

606
00:38:48,532 --> 00:38:52,132
You are the audience. Darkness.

607
00:38:52,812 --> 00:38:56,652
And from the darkness, a giant papaya.

608
00:38:57,972 --> 00:39:00,932
Dancers emerge from the papaya,

609
00:39:00,972 --> 00:39:03,292
and the dancers are all me.

610
00:39:05,052 --> 00:39:07,652
And they go to drink
from the milk of their mother,

611
00:39:07,732 --> 00:39:08,812
who is a cactus.

612
00:39:08,972 --> 00:39:10,612
But who is also me.

613
00:39:10,652 --> 00:39:14,652
And her milk is not milk but tears.

614
00:39:15,972 --> 00:39:17,092
Is it too obvious?

615
00:39:17,252 --> 00:39:20,652
I think it's just
the right amount of obvious?

616
00:39:20,772 --> 00:39:24,012
It could use some music.
Oh, what if you did like...

617
00:39:27,652 --> 00:39:29,012
Oh! And then it could go...

618
00:39:34,612 --> 00:39:36,692
And what if everything was on fire?

619
00:39:37,452 --> 00:39:39,492
Yes! Fire! Everywhere!

620
00:39:39,692 --> 00:39:43,852
Inspired! You have
the spirit of an artist.

621
00:39:45,852 --> 00:39:48,612
The dancers exit.
The music fades, the lights go out.

622
00:39:48,772 --> 00:39:51,972
And Ernesto de la Cruz
rises to the stage!

623
00:39:55,932 --> 00:39:57,012
Huh?

624
00:39:57,172 --> 00:39:59,372
He does a couple of songs,
the sun rises, everyone cheers--

625
00:39:59,532 --> 00:40:02,052
Excuse me, where's the real de la Cruz?

626
00:40:02,212 --> 00:40:04,172
Ernesto doesn't do rehearsals!

627
00:40:04,332 --> 00:40:07,772
He's too busy hosting that fancy party
at the top of his tower.

628
00:40:11,732 --> 00:40:13,652
<i>Chamaco,</i> you can't run off
on me like that.

629
00:40:13,732 --> 00:40:15,452
Stop pestering the celebrities.

630
00:40:15,532 --> 00:40:17,692
You said my
great-great-grandpa would be here!

631
00:40:17,732 --> 00:40:20,372
He's halfway across town
throwing some big party.

632
00:40:20,532 --> 00:40:23,052
That bum. Who doesn't show up
to his own rehearsal?

633
00:40:23,092 --> 00:40:25,892
If you're such good friends,
how come he didn't invite you?

634
00:40:25,972 --> 00:40:28,692
He's your great-great-grandpa,
how come he didn't invite you?

635
00:40:28,852 --> 00:40:31,652
Hey, Gustavo! You know
anything about this party?

636
00:40:32,012 --> 00:40:33,132
It's the hot ticket!

637
00:40:33,412 --> 00:40:37,252
But if you're not on the guest list,
you're never getting in, <i>Chorizo.</i>

638
00:40:37,412 --> 00:40:40,252
Hey! It's <i>Chorizo! Choricito!</i>

639
00:40:40,332 --> 00:40:41,652
A-ha. Very funny, guys. Very funny.

640
00:40:41,732 --> 00:40:42,812
<i>Chorizo?</i>

641
00:40:43,292 --> 00:40:45,092
Oh, this guy's famous!

642
00:40:45,172 --> 00:40:47,212
Go on, go on.
Ask him how he died.

643
00:40:47,412 --> 00:40:48,732
I don't want to talk about it.

644
00:40:48,932 --> 00:40:51,652
He choked on some <i>chorizo!</i>

645
00:40:54,212 --> 00:40:55,772
I didn't choke, okay?

646
00:40:55,852 --> 00:40:57,652
I got food poisoning
which is a big difference.

647
00:40:59,052 --> 00:41:00,492
This is why I don't like musicians.

648
00:41:00,612 --> 00:41:02,172
Bunch of self-important jerks.

649
00:41:02,332 --> 00:41:04,612
-Hey! I'm a musician!
-You are?

650
00:41:05,132 --> 00:41:07,412
If you really want to get to Ernesto,

651
00:41:07,532 --> 00:41:08,892
there is that music competition...

652
00:41:09,052 --> 00:41:10,732
at the Plaza de la Cruz.

653
00:41:10,772 --> 00:41:12,892
Winner gets to play at his party.

654
00:41:14,292 --> 00:41:17,172
No, no. <i>Chamaco,</i>
you're <i>loco</i> if you think--

655
00:41:17,292 --> 00:41:19,452
I need to get
my great-great-grandfather's blessing!

656
00:41:19,532 --> 00:41:21,292
You know where I can get a guitar?

657
00:41:22,132 --> 00:41:25,132
I know a guy.

658
00:41:36,932 --> 00:41:39,892
Have you found him, Pepita?
Have you found our boy?

659
00:41:41,452 --> 00:41:43,572
- A footprint!
- It's a Rivera boot.

660
00:41:44,052 --> 00:41:45,772
-Size seven!
-And a half.

661
00:41:45,932 --> 00:41:48,132
-Pronated.
-Miguel.

662
00:41:57,932 --> 00:41:59,572
Why the heck would you
want to be a musician?

663
00:41:59,732 --> 00:42:01,332
My great-great-grandpa
was a musician!

664
00:42:01,412 --> 00:42:03,172
Who spent his life
performing like a monkey

665
00:42:03,252 --> 00:42:04,652
for complete strangers.

666
00:42:05,012 --> 00:42:07,332
No thank you.
No! <i>Guácala!</i>

667
00:42:07,492 --> 00:42:09,292
What do you know?

668
00:42:09,332 --> 00:42:11,452
So, how far is this guitar anyway?

669
00:42:11,612 --> 00:42:12,652
We're almost there.

670
00:42:17,852 --> 00:42:19,172
Keep up, <i>chamaco.</i> Come on.

671
00:42:28,172 --> 00:42:32,652
- Cousin Héctor!
- Hey! These guys! Hey, <i>Tío!</i>

672
00:42:32,812 --> 00:42:33,852
<i>¿Qué onda?</i>

673
00:42:33,932 --> 00:42:35,492
These people are all your family?

674
00:42:35,532 --> 00:42:36,652
Uh...

675
00:42:36,692 --> 00:42:40,012
In a way. We're all the ones
with no photos or <i>ofrendas.</i>

676
00:42:40,212 --> 00:42:42,692
No family to go home to.
Nearly forgotten, you know?

677
00:42:43,372 --> 00:42:47,172
So, we all call each other cousin,
or <i>tío,</i> or whatever.

678
00:42:51,812 --> 00:42:54,052
-Héctor!
<i>-Tía</i> Chelo!

679
00:42:56,212 --> 00:42:58,132
<i>Muchas gracias!</i>

680
00:42:58,292 --> 00:43:00,532
Hey! Save some for me!
Is Chicharrón around?

681
00:43:00,692 --> 00:43:02,052
Eh, in the bungalow.

682
00:43:02,132 --> 00:43:04,372
I don't know if he's
in the mood for visitors.

683
00:43:04,532 --> 00:43:07,572
Who doesn't like
a visit from Cousin Héctor?

684
00:43:16,892 --> 00:43:18,572
<i>Buenas noches,</i> Chicharrón!

685
00:43:18,732 --> 00:43:21,052
I don't want to see
your stupid face, Héctor.

686
00:43:21,252 --> 00:43:23,252
Come on. It's <i>Día de Muertos.</i>

687
00:43:23,412 --> 00:43:24,652
I brought you a little offering.

688
00:43:24,812 --> 00:43:26,972
-Get out of here.
-I would, Cheech.

689
00:43:27,092 --> 00:43:29,332
But the thing is,
me and my friend, Miguel...

690
00:43:30,652 --> 00:43:32,452
We really need to borrow your guitar.

691
00:43:32,572 --> 00:43:34,172
-My guitar?
-Yes.

692
00:43:34,252 --> 00:43:36,572
My prized beloved guitar?

693
00:43:36,692 --> 00:43:38,012
I promise we'll bring it right back.

694
00:43:38,212 --> 00:43:40,332
Like the time you promised
to bring back my van?

695
00:43:40,772 --> 00:43:42,012
-Uh...
-Or my mini-fridge?

696
00:43:42,292 --> 00:43:43,892
-Ah, you see--
-Or my good napkins?

697
00:43:44,052 --> 00:43:45,692
My lasso? My femur?

698
00:43:45,812 --> 00:43:47,052
Well, no, not like those times.

699
00:43:47,092 --> 00:43:49,332
Where is my femur? You--

700
00:43:49,492 --> 00:43:50,532
Whoa, whoa.

701
00:43:51,412 --> 00:43:55,052
- You okay, <i>amigo?</i>
- I'm fading, Héctor.

702
00:43:55,932 --> 00:43:58,412
I can feel it.

703
00:43:58,452 --> 00:44:01,252
I couldn't even play
that thing if I wanted to.

704
00:44:04,732 --> 00:44:07,092
You play me something.

705
00:44:07,372 --> 00:44:09,412
No. You know
I don't play anymore, Cheech.

706
00:44:09,452 --> 00:44:10,732
The guitar is for the kid.

707
